{
  "texts": [
    "The SE state has a higher MMD compared to other classes in the target training data, as it behaves differently to the damage state data; the stiffening effect increases the stiffness, whereas, the damage states introduce a reduction in stiffness.",
    "The effect of these different behaviors is also evident in Figure 3.",
    "The information in Figure 16 can, therefore, aid feature selection at the start of the analysis chain to discount SE data from the transfer learning process.",
    "This is the first article in the context of SHM that investigated the use of domain adaptation for damage localisation when there exists discrepancies between the damage states in the labeled source structure and unlabelled target structure, under natural excitations.",
    "Differences such as severity and type of damage between source and target domains are likely in realistic applications of transfer learning, outside of laboratory environments."
  ]
}